   <div id="abbreviationsunderstood-notes" type="gl-notes">
      <head>Notes</head>
      <list type="unordered">

         <item>An <tag>abbr</tag> element within the <tag>expan</tag> containing the abbreviated
            form of the word is available but optional. It may be useful when the abbreviation
            contains additional markers not in the expanded form (cf. <ref target="EncEx-3"
               evaluate="all" targOrder="Y">Augg</ref> and <ref target="EncEx-4" evaluate="all"
               targOrder="Y">pr.</ref> above), but might require additional linking in cases where
            the abbreviation must be expanded by interpolation (<ref target="EncEx-2" evaluate="all"
               targOrder="Y">cf. co(n)s(ul)</ref>)</item>
         <item>When the abbreviated form contains markers not in the expanded form, such as <ref
               target="EncEx-3" evaluate="all" targOrder="Y">additional letters</ref> or <ref
               target="EncEx-4" evaluate="all" targOrder="Y">punctuation</ref>, best practice is to
            put these in <tag>am</tag> (abbreviation marker) elements, which the standard
            stylesheets will omit when rendering the expanded form.</item>
         <item>Abbreviated phrases (<abbr expan="for example = exempli gratia">e.g.</abbr>, <foreign
               lang="la">D(is) M(anibus)</foreign>) should properly be marked-up as a group, as
            illustrated in <ref target="EncEx-5" evaluate="all" targOrder="Y">the example
            above</ref>, but marking them as single words is not incorrect (see <ref
               target="EncEx-6" evaluate="all" targOrder="Y">the second example</ref>).</item>

      </list>
   </div>
   <div id="abbreviationsunderstood-questions" type="gl-questions">
